Forrest W. Crawford

Prediction

We have talked about fitting models to data, making their output and dynamics match what we observe empirically in the real world.

But models are most useful, and most dangerous, when we use them to generalize about circumstances we have not yet seen.

This could mean a different time, a different population, different interventions, or different parameter inputs.

Running models forward

Suppose you have parameterized a model \(y(t|\theta)\) with parameters \(\theta\) and calibrated it to some time range \([0,T]\).

You might wish to:

  • Predict \(y(t)\) for \(t>T\).

Sensitivity analysis

Sensitivity analysis is the process of learning about how your model output depends on its input parameters.

  • Sensitivity to initial conditions
  • Sensitivity to parameter values
  • Sensitivity to intervention effects

Example SIR ODE system

Example: sensitivity to compartment starting values

\[\tilde{S}(0) \sim \text{Uniform}(0,1)\] \[\tilde{I}(0) = 1-\tilde{S}(0)\] \[\tilde{R}(0)=0 \]

  run_sir = function(xstart,params) {
    out <- as.data.frame( lsoda(xstart, times, sir.model, params) )
  }

  plot(out$time, out$S, ylab="Population proportion", xlab="Time", bty="n", ylim=c(0,1), type="n") 
  #lines(out$time, out$I, col="red", lwd=2) 
  #lines(out$time, out$R, col="blue", lwd=2)

  legend(100,0.5, c("S(t)", "I(t)", "R(t)"), lty=1, lwd=2, col=c("green", "red", "blue"))

  nsim = 100
  for(j in 1:nsim) {
    s_j = runif(1)
    xstart_j = c(S=s_j, I=1-s_j, R=0)
    out_j = run_sir(xstart_j, params)
    lines(out_j$time, out_j$S, col=rgb(0,1,0,alpha=0.1))
    lines(out_j$time, out_j$I, col=rgb(1,0,0,alpha=0.1))
    lines(out_j$time, out_j$R, col=rgb(0,0,1,alpha=0.1))
  }

Example: sensitivity to parameter values

\(\tilde\beta \sim \text{Normal}(\beta,0.03)\) \(\tilde\gamma \sim \text{Normal}(\gamma,0.03)\)

  plot(out$time, out$S, ylab="Population proportion", xlab="Time", bty="n", ylim=c(0,1), type="n") 
  legend(100,0.5, c("S(t)", "I(t)", "R(t)"), lty=1, lwd=2, col=c("green", "red", "blue"))

  nsim = 100
  for(j in 1:nsim) {
    params_j = rnorm(2, params, 0.03)
    params_j = pmin(params_j,1)
    params_j = pmax(params_j,0)
    names(params_j) = c("beta", "gamma")
    out_j = run_sir(xstart, params_j)
    lines(out_j$time, out_j$S, col=rgb(0,1,0,alpha=0.1))
    lines(out_j$time, out_j$I, col=rgb(1,0,0,alpha=0.1))
    lines(out_j$time, out_j$R, col=rgb(0,0,1,alpha=0.1))
  }
